{
  "texts": [
    "The scaling law [21] has inspired researchers to realize that the size of the model has a significant impact on its performance and effectiveness.",
    "Therefore, they have started to investigate this effect by training larger pre-trained models.",
    "Despite the primary change of increasing in the number of parameters (with these models still utilizing similar architectures and pre-training tasks), these large-scale pre-trained language models exhibit performance characteristics completely distinct from their relatively smaller counterparts (e.g., 330 M-parameter BERT and 175B-parameter GPT-3 [51]), demonstrating surprising abilities in solving a series of complex tasks.",
    "Therefore, models with a larger number of parameters compared to PLMs are referred to as \"large language models\" [28,[51][52][53] in the NLP community.",
    "A notable difference between LLMs and PLMs is the presence of \"emergent abilities,\" referring to capacities absent in PLMs yet arising in LLMs [20]."
  ]
}